// Criminal Procedure Code [Act 593] — CONDITIONAL-RIGHTS cluster: protections
// that switch ON because of who the citizen is (woman, minor, pregnant,
// disabled, elderly) plus the two arrest-clock rights the cluster brief
// assigns here (s28A rights on arrest, s117 remand before a Magistrate).
// The "setup turn" set: s19(2) a woman may only be searched by a woman with
// strict regard to decency; s28A inform-relative + consult-lawyer rights
// before questioning; s117 detention past 24 hours needs a Magistrate and
// caps remand at 4+3 / 7+7 days; s275 a pregnant woman cannot be sentenced
// to death (life imprisonment instead); s289 whipping exemptions (females,
// males sentenced to death, males over fifty except certain sexual
// offences); s388(1) proviso — court MAY bail a person under sixteen, any
// woman, or any sick or infirm person even for offences punishable with
// death/life; Fourth Schedule para 3 (body-search conduct: same-sex officer,
// gender-in-doubt procedure, second same-sex officer for strip/intimate/
// intrusive, religious sensitivity on scarf/headdress removal, and para
// 3(2)(h) accommodations when the person is pregnant, elderly or disabled);
// Fourth Schedule para 12(d) (no squat during intimate search where the
// person is incapable due to health/physical condition or appears to be or
// CLAIMS to be pregnant).
// COLLISION GUARD: a sibling file (cpc.jsonl) carries the general
// search/arrest sections (s15, s20-region, s23, s62, s116-region). This file
// deliberately stays off those; s19 sits adjacent to that region but its
// operative right is condition-triggered (search of women) so it lives here.
// The Fourth Schedule chunks are slices of the schedule made under s20A —
// refs point at CPC s20A which may not exist as a chunk yet (coverage gap
// for the keeper's ledger, not a failure).
// SCHEDULE CITATION NOTE (for the keeper): the two Fourth Schedule chunks
// use section "Fourth Schedule" with the paragraph in the subsection field —
// the id/section convention has no schedule precedent yet; flagging rather
// than inventing silently.
// AUTHORITY: PDRM (CPC police powers). s275/s289/s388 are court-applied but
// arise from PDRM-lane criminal process — single-authority field limitation,
// tagged PDRM per cluster brief. state:ALL — federal.
// EN text pdftotext-extracted from the official AGC reprint "As at
// 1 October 2022" (corpus/raw/act593/en.pdftotext.txt). Per keeper ruling
// (same treatment as PA s26): the inline * amendment marker the reprint
// prints before "imprisonment for life" in s275 is STRIPPED — bare enacted
// text only; the "*NOTE—..." editorial footnote it points to (life = 30
// years, Act 345) is excluded as annotation, not operative law. This 2022
// consolidation predates the 2023 death-penalty reform acts — s275 text is
// the pre-reform wording, re-derived and confirmed unchanged vs 2017.
// Multi-space runs collapsed to single spaces; enumerated
// items rejoined one per line; words/punctuation/numbering untouched
// (including the reprint's own quirks, e.g. s28A(6) "paragraph 2(b)" and the
// U+2015 horizontal bar "―" the reprint uses in s28A).
// All chunks verified:false until the corpus-keeper's word-for-word check.
{"id": "CPC-s19-en-0", "authority": "PDRM", "statute": "Criminal Procedure Code", "statute_abbr": "CPC", "act_number": "593", "state": "ALL", "section": "19", "kind": "procedure", "heading": "No unnecessary restraint and mode of searching women", "lang": "en", "text": "19. (1) The person arrested shall not be subjected to more restraint than is necessary to prevent his escape.\n(2) Whenever it is necessary to cause a woman to be searched the search shall be made by another woman with strict regard to decency.", "source_url": "https://lom.agc.gov.my/act-detail.php?language=BI&act=593", "as_at": "2022-10-01", "verified": true}
{"id": "CPC-s28A-en-0", "authority": "PDRM", "statute": "Criminal Procedure Code", "statute_abbr": "CPC", "act_number": "593", "state": "ALL", "section": "28A", "kind": "procedure", "refs": [{"statute": "CPC", "section": "117"}], "heading": "Rights of person arrested", "lang": "en", "text": "28A. (1) A person arrested without a warrant shall be informed as soon as may be of the grounds of his arrest by the police officer making the arrest.\n(2) A police officer shall, before commencing any form of questioning or recording of any statement from the person arrested, inform the person that he may―\n(a) communicate or attempt to communicate, with a relative or friend to inform of his whereabouts; and\n(b) communicate or attempt to communicate and consult with a legal practitioner of his choice.\n(3) Where the person arrested wishes to communicate or attempt to communicate with the persons referred to in paragraphs (2)(a) and (b), the police officer shall, as soon as may be, allow the arrested person to do so.\n(4) Where the person arrested has requested for a legal practitioner to be consulted, the police officer shall allow a reasonable time―\n(a) for the legal practitioner to be present to meet the person arrested at his place of detention; and\n(b) for the consultation to take place.\n(5) The consultation under subsection (4) shall be within the sight of a police officer and in circumstances, in so far as practicable, where their communication will not be overheard.\n(6) The police officer shall defer any questioning or recording of any statement from the person arrested for a reasonable time until the communication or attempted communication under paragraph 2(b) or the consultation under subsection (4) has been made.\n(7) The police officer shall provide reasonable facilities for the communication and consultation under this section and all such facilities provided shall be free of charge.\n(8) The requirements under subsections (2), (3), (4), (5), (6) and (7) shall not apply where the police officer reasonably believes that―\n(a) compliance with any of the requirements is likely to result in―\n(i) an accomplice of the person arrested taking steps to avoid apprehension; or\n(ii) the concealment, fabrication or destruction of evidence or the intimidation of a witness; or\n(b) having regard to the safety of other persons the questioning or recording of any statement is so urgent that it should not be delayed.\n(9) Subsection (8) shall only apply upon authorization by a police officer not below the rank of Deputy Superintendent of Police.\n(10) The police officer giving the authorization under subsection (9) shall record the grounds of belief of the police officer that the conditions specified under subsection (8) will arise and such record shall be made as soon as practicable.\n(11) The investigating officer shall comply with the requirements under subsections (2), (3), (4), (5), (6) and (7) as soon as possible after the conditions specified under subsection (8) have ceased to apply where the person arrested is still under detention under this section or under section 117.", "source_url": "https://lom.agc.gov.my/act-detail.php?language=BI&act=593", "as_at": "2022-10-01", "verified": true}
{"id": "CPC-s117-en-0", "authority": "PDRM", "statute": "Criminal Procedure Code", "statute_abbr": "CPC", "act_number": "593", "state": "ALL", "section": "117", "kind": "procedure", "refs": [{"statute": "CPC", "section": "28"}], "heading": "Procedure where investigation cannot be completed within twenty-four hours", "lang": "en", "text": "117. (1) Whenever any person is arrested and detained in custody and it appears that the investigation cannot be completed within the period of twenty-four hours fixed by section 28 and there are grounds for believing that the accusation or information is well founded the police officer making the investigation shall immediately transmit to a Magistrate a copy of the entries in the diary hereinafter prescribed relating to the case and shall at the same time produce the accused before the Magistrate.\n(1A) The Public Prosecutor may appear in any application made under this section.\n(2) The Magistrate before whom an accused person is produced under this section may, whether he has or has no jurisdiction to try the case, authorize the detention of the accused in such custody as follows:\n(a) if the offence which is being investigated is punishable with imprisonment of less than fourteen years, the detention shall not be more than four days on the first application and shall not be more than three days on the second application; or\n(b) if the offence which is being investigated is punishable with death or imprisonment of fourteen years or more, the detention shall not be more than seven days on the first application and shall not be more than seven days on the second application.\n(3) The officer making the investigation shall state in the copy of the entries in the diary referred to in subsection (1), any period of detention of the accused immediately prior to the application, whether or not such detention relates to the application.\n(4) The Magistrate, in deciding the period of detention of the accused person, shall take into consideration any detention period immediately prior to the application, whether or not such detention relates to the application.\n(5) The Magistrate in deciding the period of detention of the accused shall allow representations to be made either by the accused himself or through a counsel of his choice.\n(6) If the Magistrate has no jurisdiction to try the case and considers further detention unnecessary he may order the accused person to be produced before a Magistrate having such jurisdiction or, if the case is triable only by the High Court, before himself or another Magistrate having jurisdiction with a view to transmission for trial by the High Court.\n(7) A Magistrate authorizing under this section detention in the custody of the police shall record his reasons for so doing.", "source_url": "https://lom.agc.gov.my/act-detail.php?language=BI&act=593", "as_at": "2022-10-01", "verified": true}
{"id": "CPC-s275-en-0", "authority": "PDRM", "statute": "Criminal Procedure Code", "statute_abbr": "CPC", "act_number": "593", "state": "ALL", "section": "275", "kind": "procedure", "heading": "Sentence of death not to be passed on pregnant woman", "lang": "en", "text": "275. Where a woman convicted of an offence punishable with death is alleged to be pregnant, or where the Court before whom a woman is so convicted thinks fit, the Court shall direct one or more medical practitioners to be sworn to examine that woman in some private place and to enquire whether she is pregnant or not, and if upon the report of any of them it appears that she is pregnant the sentence to be passed upon her shall be a sentence of imprisonment for life instead of sentence of death.", "source_url": "https://lom.agc.gov.my/act-detail.php?language=BI&act=593", "as_at": "2022-10-01", "verified": true}
{"id": "CPC-s289-en-0", "authority": "PDRM", "statute": "Criminal Procedure Code", "statute_abbr": "CPC", "act_number": "593", "state": "ALL", "section": "289", "kind": "penalty", "heading": "Sentence of whipping forbidden in certain cases", "lang": "en", "text": "289. No sentence of whipping shall be executed by instalments, and none of the following persons shall be punishable with whipping:\n(a) females;\n(b) males sentenced to death;\n(c) males whom the Court considers to be more than fifty years of age, except males sentenced to whipping under section 376, 377C, 377CA or 377E of the Penal Code.", "source_url": "https://lom.agc.gov.my/act-detail.php?language=BI&act=593", "as_at": "2022-10-01", "verified": true}
{"id": "CPC-s388-en-0", "authority": "PDRM", "statute": "Criminal Procedure Code", "statute_abbr": "CPC", "act_number": "593", "state": "ALL", "section": "388", "subsection": "388(1)", "kind": "procedure", "heading": "When person accused of non-bailable offence may be released on bail", "lang": "en", "text": "388. (1) When any person accused of any non-bailable offence is arrested or detained without warrant by a police officer or appears or is brought before a Court, he may be released on bail by the Officer in charge of the Police District or by that Court, but he shall not be so released if there appears reasonable grounds for believing that he has been guilty of an offence punishable with death or imprisonment for life:\nProvided that the Court may direct that any person under the age of sixteen years or any woman or any sick or infirm person accused of such an offence be released on bail.", "source_url": "https://lom.agc.gov.my/act-detail.php?language=BI&act=593", "as_at": "2022-10-01", "verified": true}
{"id": "CPC-sch4-para3-en-0", "authority": "PDRM", "statute": "Criminal Procedure Code", "statute_abbr": "CPC", "act_number": "593", "state": "ALL", "section": "Fourth Schedule", "subsection": "Fourth Schedule para 3", "kind": "procedure", "refs": [{"statute": "CPC", "section": "20A"}, {"statute": "CPC", "section": "19"}], "heading": "General conduct of officer during search", "lang": "en", "text": "3. (1) An officer conducting a body search shall do so in a professional manner and have the highest regard for the dignity of the person arrested.\n(2) The officer shall comply strictly with the following procedure:\n(a) before any search is commenced, the officer shall introduce himself to the person arrested and shall be courteous, professional and shall not use unnecessary or demeaning language or remarks against the person arrested and shall cause minimal embarrassment to the person;\n(b) the search shall not be more extensive than necessary to ascertain the existence of harmful or unlawful articles believed to be concealed on the person arrested;\n(c) the officer conducting the search shall be of the same sex as the person arrested with strict regard to decency;\n(d) where the gender of the person arrested is in doubt, his gender shall be determined by way of an interview or through his identification card or birth certificate before a search is conducted by an appropriate officer with strict regard to decency;\n(e) for strip, intimate and intrusive search, a second officer who is of the same sex of the person arrested shall be present during the search;\n(f) no officer shall disclose to the public any blemish, flaw or defect of body parts found on the body of the person arrested during the cause of the search;\n(g) in the course of a search, the officer shall respect—\n(i) the religious and cultural sensitivities; and\n(ii) the physical, psychological, medical and mental characteristics,\nof a person arrested. In cases involving the removal of a female’s scarf or male headdress, religious and cultural sensitivity approach shall be adopted;\n(h) when a person arrested is pregnant, elderly or a person with disabilities, the search shall be conducted in a proper manner taking into consideration the state of the person’s medical and physical condition.", "source_url": "https://lom.agc.gov.my/act-detail.php?language=BI&act=593", "as_at": "2022-10-01", "verified": true}
{"id": "CPC-sch4-para12-en-0", "authority": "PDRM", "statute": "Criminal Procedure Code", "statute_abbr": "CPC", "act_number": "593", "state": "ALL", "section": "Fourth Schedule", "subsection": "Fourth Schedule para 12(d)", "kind": "procedure", "refs": [{"statute": "CPC", "section": "20A"}], "heading": "Procedure on intimate search", "lang": "en", "text": "(d) where the officer considers that the person arrested is incapable of doing the squat due to the health, physical conditions or appears to be or claims to be pregnant, the squat shall not be performed;", "source_url": "https://lom.agc.gov.my/act-detail.php?language=BI&act=593", "as_at": "2022-10-01", "verified": true}
